; the post-fix validation run completed in 95 seconds, which is within the SLA and below the 200-second threshold. The rerun also validated product_master reconciliation, source row count, and AutoRCA evidence collection so the incident could be closed as resolved. The measured fix reduced runtime by 62.45 percent for this incident, and the estimated improvement based on historical optimized product-load performance is 93.19 percent.","The SLA breach delayed product data availability beyond the expected 200 seconds (3 minutes 20 seconds) processing window. The failed run completed or failed after 253 seconds instead of within 200 seconds, delaying catalog refresh, downstream product export, pricing visibility, inventory synchronization, or SLA-based operational reporting depending on the consuming system. Because product_master is a shared retail reference table, stale data exposure was possible until the corrected run completed and row-count reconciliation passed. The missed SLA should be read as a 53-second breach beyond the expected 200-second processing target for a 1250000-row product workload.","Persist expected_sla_seconds=200, actual_elapsed_seconds, sla_delay_seconds, row_count, dag_id, task_id, run_id, and load phase timings into the incident evidence collected by AutoRCA. The RAG knowledge base should include the expected SLA text inside the RCA narrative so future SLA_MISS incidents can retrieve the correct target without requiring a new schema column. Add phase-level metrics for file read, validation, COPY or merge, export, and callback duration, then alert when any phase trends toward breaching the 200 seconds (3 minutes 20 seconds) target. Future AutoRCA retrieval should prioritize incidents with failure_pattern=sla_miss_formatting_error_after_large_csv_read, record_volume near 1250000, insert_method=staged_copy_with_python_callback, and SLA threshold 200 seconds.",Y,1250000,253,4940.71,200,53,staged_copy_with_python_callback,50000,5,sla_miss_formatti